HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 862
By Sexton
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Natalie Leach Haslam of
Knoxville.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Natalie Leach Haslam; and
WHEREAS, Natalie Leach Haslam was a beloved Tennessean whose life of service,
generosity, and civic leadership left an indelible mark on her community, her alma mater, and
the cultural life of this State; and
WHEREAS, born in 1931 to Dr. Robert Swepson and Jennie Belle Boyden, Natalie
Haslam was raised in the Sequoyah Hills neighborhood of Knoxville and remained a lifelong
parishioner of St. John's Cathedral; and
WHEREAS, Mrs. Haslam graduated from the University of Tennessee (UT) in 1952 with
a degree in liberal arts and was named Miss Tennessee 1951–1952 during her time as a
student; she remained a devoted supporter of the university throughout her life, and in 2024, the
College of Music was named in her honor in recognition of her extraordinary commitment to the
arts and higher education; and
WHEREAS, Natalie Haslam gave generously of her time and resources in service to
numerous civic and cultural organizations, including the Knoxville Symphony Society, East
Tennessee Foundation, East Tennessee Historical Society, Knoxville Garden Club, Arts and
Cultural Alliance of Greater Knoxville, Friends of the Great Smoky Mountains National Park,
Tennessee Arts Commission, Zoo Knoxville, Maryville College, Child and Family Services, the
Wellness Community, the Webb School of Knoxville, and the Junior League of Knoxville; and
WHEREAS, at her alma mater, Mrs. Haslam served on the Library Society Board,
College of Arts and Sciences Board of Visitors, Friends of the UT Gardens, UT Chancellor's
HJR0862
011995
- 1 -

Circle, Chancellor's Associates, and UT Alliance of Women Philanthropists Executive Board;
and
WHEREAS, a devoted supporter of the arts, Mrs. Haslam was the first woman to serve
as president of the Knoxville Symphony Orchestra, and her generosity helped shape the
region's artistic and educational landscape for future generations; and
WHEREAS, in recognition of her enduring service and civic contributions, Natalie
Haslam was named the University of Tennessee's Volunteer of the Year in 1992 and, alongside
her husband, Jim Haslam, was named a Distinguished Alumnus of the university in 2009; she
was also recognized as East Tennessean of the Year by the East Tennessee Historical Society
in 2018; and
WHEREAS, above all else, Mrs. Haslam was deeply devoted to her family; she is
survived by her loving husband of fifty years, James A. "Jim" Haslam II; daughters, Jennie (Rob)
McCabe, Susan (Chip) Robie, and Carol Pattison; stepchildren, Jimmy (Dee) Haslam, Ann
Haslam (Steve) Bailey, and Governor Bill (Crissy) Haslam; and her grandchildren and great-
grandchildren, all of whom brought her great pride and joy; and
WHEREAS, Natalie Haslam leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in
public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all her chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that we pause to remember the bountiful life of this remarkable
woman, whose compassion, vision, and dedication to service enriched the lives of so many;
now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Natalie Leach Haslam, reflecting fondly upon her
impeccable character, her lifetime of leadership and generosity, and her stalwart commitment to
living the examined life with courage and conviction.
- 2 - 011995

BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mrs. Haslam.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
